<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-240-108  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 240 108.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Micro  Feb 1990 v10 n1 p4(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Cocom: the next wall to fall? (Coordinating committee onMultilateral Export Controls) (Micro World) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kirrman, Hubert.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Coordination Committee on Multilateral Export Controls (Cocom)is a voluntary organization formed by NATO during the Cold War toprevent Communist governments from accessing other countries' hightechnology.andP;  Cuba, Iran, The Philippines and South Africa werelater added to the list.andP;  Cocom members include all NATO countriesexcept Iceland, Japan and France.andP;  Decisions are reached byUnanimous agreement.andP;  The list of banned goods, which includesdRAM chips, EPROMs, microprocessors larger than eight bits,floating point processors and more.andP;  The list has grownconsiderably over the last ten years, and is purged infrequently.andO;Changes depend on the political climate.andP;  Most complaints aboutthe rules arise from the European industrial community, especiallyin West Germany.andP;  US firms claim that Glasnost and perestroikahave increased technology smuggling.andP;  Calls for dramatic changeshave come from several countries.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Coordinating Committee for Multilateral Export ControlsRegulationExportOutlook.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>